content.description:
Liebacking moves up to a fun and excited roof pull.

"The name came about because Rick Taylor had just subcribed to mail order his coffee from Starbucks and was real excited about it." - Jason Stevens
content.protection: Five bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: Follows the right corner on the left formation.

content.description: The route to do in New Canyon. Interesting puzzle solving and moving back on forth on good, but not great holds. At certain times of the year, this route smells exactly like a bookmobile.
content.protection: A section of angle iron in the crack followed by six bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: The leftmost route on the wall. Look for a blocky chimney with three foot sections of angle iron on it and go right.

content.description: Same start as "Don't Kick the Baby", but it moves straight up the black rock on pockets, slopers, and edges after the third bolt.
content.protection: Five bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: Starts in the left corner of the right formation.

content.description: Great pockets that dead end, forcing you back into a steep corner and up to a nice crack.
content.protection: Five bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: Find a hard south facing corner, and walk left 15-20 feet. The route follows the arete.

content.description: Funky corner moves with handjams that to quote Jason, will make you want to kick something. Stay left at the roof.
content.protection: Four bolts to a cold-shut anchors.
content.location: Starts in the left corner of the right formation.

content.description: Fun jug pull with a cool undercling move around the middle. This route's downfall would be the inevitable grabbing of a bat crap covered hold. Seriously... theres a lot of poo.
content.protection: Five bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: Goes up the blocky face on the center right formation. Look for the bat poop.

content.description: Casual climbing to the last bolt, where you climb on the left side grabbing bad pinches and small underclings. Tough to onsight.
content.protection: Four bolts to a chain anchor.
content.location: Up the face between the arete and the corner.
